# Architecture and Optimization Decisions

## System Architecture

The project follows a modular backend architecture built using FastAPI and PostgreSQL.

The system is divided into the following layers:

### 1. Data Generation Layer

A data generation script was created using the Faker library to generate:

* 100,000 Customers
* 1,000,000 Orders
* 200,000 Refunds

A reproducible random seed was used to ensure the same dataset can be generated repeatedly.

---

### 2. Mock API Layer

FastAPI APIs were created to expose:

* Customers
* Orders
* Refunds

Pagination was implemented using page and page_size parameters to efficiently serve large datasets without loading all records into memory.

---

### 3. Ingestion Service

A separate ingestion service was implemented to:

* Pull data from paginated APIs
* Process records in batches
* Store data into PostgreSQL

The ingestion service continuously fetches paginated data until no records remain.

---

### 4. Analytics Layer

Analytics APIs were developed for:

* Total Orders
* Total Revenue
* Total Refunds
* Net Revenue
* Average Order Value
* Repeat Customer Revenue
* Revenue Trends
* Top Customers by Spend

The analytics layer uses SQL aggregation functions such as:

* COUNT
* SUM
* AVG
* GROUP BY
* ORDER BY

to efficiently process large datasets directly inside PostgreSQL.

---

# Optimization Decisions

## Pagination

Pagination was implemented across APIs to reduce payload size and improve API response time.

Formula used:

\text{offset}=(\text{page}-1)\times\text{page_size}

This prevents loading massive datasets into memory at once.

---

## Database Optimization

### Indexing

Indexes were added on frequently queried columns such as:

* customer_id
* order_id
* created_at

This improves filtering, joins, and aggregation query performance.

---

## Efficient Aggregations

Instead of processing records in Python, analytics calculations were pushed to PostgreSQL using SQL aggregation functions.

This significantly reduced API processing time.

---

## Batch Processing

The ingestion service processes records in chunks rather than loading the entire dataset into memory.

This improves scalability and memory efficiency.

---

## Duplicate Prevention

SQLAlchemy merge() was used during ingestion to avoid duplicate inserts and maintain data consistency.

---

## Response Time Optimization

Analytics queries were designed to execute directly in PostgreSQL to maintain response times under 2 seconds on large datasets.

---

## Modular Project Structure

The project was separated into:

* Models
* Routes
* Services
* Utilities

This improves maintainability, scalability, and code readability.

---

# Load Testing

Basic concurrent load testing was performed using Postman and multiple API requests.

The system successfully handled concurrent requests while maintaining acceptable response times.

Potential future improvements include:

* Redis caching
* Celery background jobs
* Docker containerization
* Materialized views
* Async processing
